 as exclusive elite enclaves. But in response to pressures to increase and diversify the audiences for arts institutions, elite board members act in a surprisingly open manner in terms of organizational accessibility and operations. Written with clarity and grace, Trustees of Culture will contribute significantly to our understanding of organizational governance; the politics of fundraising; elite arts participation and philanthropy; as well as the consequences of wider social policies that continue to emphasize private financial support. Ostrower's study will prove to be indispensable reading for not just sociologists of culture, but anyone interested in how the arts are financially and institutionally supported.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  acultural, powerful, wealth, income, finance, economy, economics, status, class, classism, classist, elite, artist, artistic, research, academic, scholarly, interview, fieldwork, museum, united states, usa, america, american, history, historical, organization, accessibility, operations, philanthropy, support, sociology, ethnicity, race, racism, bias, problems.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226778860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226778860/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles